    <h3 class="er-text-4xl mb:er-text-[17px] margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">Battery Capacity</h3>
    <p class="er-text-3xl mb:er-text-2xl er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        A battery's capacity is measured in
        <a
          href="https://www.e-education.psu.edu/ae868/node/896"
          class="my-link"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >watt-hours (Wh) and amp-hours (Ah)</a
        >. A watt-hour represents one watt of power delivered for one hour. For example, a 500Wh battery can
        theoretically provide 500 watts of power for one hour, or 250 watts for two hours. Amp-hours measure electric
        charge - multiply Ah by your battery's voltage to get Wh (e.g., 10Ah × 48V = 480Wh).
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="er-text-4xl mb:er-text-[17px] margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">Motor Types and Their Power Use</h3>

    <ul class="er-text-3xl mb:er-text-2xl margin-bottom-40 mb-margin-bottom-24 er-pl-10 er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed er-text-[#333]">
      <li class="margin-top-16 mb-margin-top-8">
        <b>Hub Motors:</b> Built into the wheel, these motors are common and reliable. Front-hub motors typically use
        30-50% more energy than mid-drive motors. Rear-hub motors offer better efficiency but still use 15-25% more
        power than mid-drives.
      </li>
      <li class="margin-top-16 mb-margin-top-8">
        <b>Mid-Drive Motors:</b> Mounted at the pedals, these motors are 85-95% efficient. They use the bike's gears to
        optimize power delivery, reducing battery drain on hills and varying terrain.
      </li>
    </ul>

