    <h2 class="er-text-5xl mb:er-text-4xl mb:er-leading-snug margin-bottom-20">Three Methods to Calculate E-bike Range</h2>
    <p class="er-text-3xl mb:er-text-2xl er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        With these range factors in mind, you can use the following three methods to calculate how far your e-bike will
        actually take you.
      </span>
    </p>
    <h3 class="er-text-4xl mb:er-text-[17px] margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">1. Check Real Range from Manufacturer Data</h3>
    <p class="er-text-3xl mb:er-text-2xl er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        Manufacturers conduct their range tests under carefully controlled conditions, with a 165-pound rider on flat
        terrain, no wind, and a temperature of 70°F (21°C). They also assume moderate pedaling effort throughout the
        ride. These ideal conditions rarely match real-world riding scenarios. For a realistic estimate, reduce the
        manufacturer's stated range by 20% for normal riding conditions. More challenging routes with hills and wind
        might require a 40% reduction, while extreme conditions could cut the stated range by half or more.
      </span>
    </p>

    <h3 class="er-text-4xl mb:er-text-[17px] margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">2. Calculate Range with the Basic Formula</h3>
    <p class="er-text-3xl mb:er-text-2xl er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed margin-bottom-20">
      <span>
        The fundamental formula for e-bike range is:<br>
        <b class="er-text-2xl er-p-6 er-block leading-loose"
          >Range (miles) = Battery Capacity (Watt-hours) ÷ Energy Use (Watt-hours per mile)</b
        >
        On flat terrain under ideal conditions, most e-bikes consume about 10 watt-hours per mile. This consumption
        increases to 15-20 watt-hours on mixed terrain, 20-25 watt-hours in hilly areas, and 25-30 watt-hours for
        mountain biking.
        <br>
        <br>
        For example, with a 500Wh battery on mixed terrain:
      </span>
    </p>
    <ul class="er-text-3xl mb:er-text-2xl er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed margin-bottom-20 er-pl-10 er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed er-text-[#333]">
      <li class="margin-top-16 mb-margin-top-8"><b>Best case:</b> 500Wh ÷ 15Wh/mile = 33 miles</li>
      <li class="margin-top-16 mb-margin-top-8"><b>Worst case:</b> 500Wh ÷ 20Wh/mile = 25 miles</li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="er-text-4xl mb:er-text-[17px] margin-bottom-20 margin-top-48">3. Try Online Range Calculators</h3>
    <p class="er-text-3xl mb:er-text-2xl er-leading-relaxed mb:er-leading-relaxed margin-bottom-32">
      <span>
        Many free online range calculators are available on e-bike manufacturer websites and independent cycling platforms. These tools automatically handle complex calculations and provide quick, customized range estimates. Simply input your e-bike's specifications and riding conditions into the calculator's interface.
<br><br>While these tools offer convenience, their accuracy depends on the quality of your input data. For the most reliable results, compare estimates from multiple calculators and cross-reference them with the basic watt-hours formula. For safety, always add a 20% buffer to your calculated range when planning rides.

      </span>
    </p>

